## Setup

### Objective

The purpose of this phase is to build a controlled Linux environment that will be used to simulate attacks, monitor activity, and implement security controls.

This environment serves as the foundation for all subsequent attack, detection, and defense activities.

---

### Environment Overview

Component        Description
---------------  --------------------------
Target System    Ubuntu Server
Attacker System  Kali Linux
Access Method    SSH
Network Type     Same network (VM or LAN)

---

### Step 1 — Install Ubuntu Server

Install Ubuntu Server on a virtual machine (VirtualBox, VMware) or physical system.

Recommended configuration:

- 2 CPU cores  
- 2 GB RAM (minimum)  
- 20 GB storage  

During installation:

- Create a default user  
- Enable OpenSSH server if prompted  

---

### Step 2 — Create Secure User

Create a dedicated user for testing authentication and attack simulation.

sudo adduser secureuser  

Verify user creation:

cat /etc/passwd | grep secureuser  

Example output:

secureuser:x:1001:1001:,,,:/home/secureuser:/bin/bash  

---

### Step 3 — Install and Enable SSH

Ensure SSH service is installed and running.

sudo apt update  
sudo apt install openssh-server -y  

Check service status:

sudo systemctl status ssh  

If not running:

sudo systemctl start ssh  

---

### Step 4 — Identify Target IP Address

Obtain the IP address of the Ubuntu server.

ip a  

Look for:

inet <IP_ADDRESS>  

Example:

inet 192.168.0.15  

---

### Step 5 — Test SSH Connectivity

From the attacker machine (Kali Linux), initiate an SSH connection:

ssh secureuser@<target-ip>  

Successful login confirms connectivity.

Example login session:

![SSH Login](../screenshots/day1/ssh-login.png)

---

### Step 6 — Enable Logging Visibility

Monitor authentication logs in real time:

sudo tail -f /var/log/auth.log  

This allows observation of:

- Successful login attempts  
- Failed login attempts  
- Source IP addresses  

Example log output:

![Auth Log Monitoring](../screenshots/day1/auth-log.png)

---

### Step 7 — Validate Logging Behavior

Perform:

- A successful login  
- A failed login attempt  

Verify logs update in real time.

Expected entries:

- Accepted password  
- Failed password  

---

### Validation

The setup phase is successful when:

- SSH login works from the attacker system  
- The secureuser account exists and authenticates correctly  
- Logs are actively updating in /var/log/auth.log  
- The system is reachable via IP  

---

### Outcome

At the end of this phase, the environment includes:

- A functioning Linux target system  
- Remote access via SSH  
- Real-time log visibility  

This system is now prepared for attack simulation and security testing.
